{{Infobox Stadium | stadium_name = Great Manmade River Stadium | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Tripoli]], [[Libya]] | built = 1999-2000<ref name="gmr_stad">[http://www.goalzz.com/main.aspx?showstadiums=1&searchcountry=LY&stadium=4648 Information at goalzz.com]</ref> | opened = 17 May 2000<ref name="gmr_stad"/> | coordinates = {{coord|32|51|35|N|13|8|13|E|display=it}}<ref name="gmr_stad"/> | renovated = | owner = [[Libyan Football Federation]] | operator = Tripoli clubs | surface = [[Artificial turf]]<ref name="gmr_stad"/> | tenants = | seating_capacity = 20,000<ref name="gmr_stad"/> | dimensions = }}
The '''Great Manmade River Stadium''' ('''GMR''' or '''GMMR''' stadium) is a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football stadium]] situated just a few metres away from the [[11 June Stadium]] in the heart of [[Tripoli]]'s sporting city. The stadium is named after the [[Great Manmade River]]. The stadium has a capacity of around 20,000 and is currently the home of [[Libyan Premier League]] clubs [[Alwahda (Tripoli)|Al Wahda]], [[Attersana S.C.|Al Tersana]] and [[Alamn Alaam]].
The stadium was opened on 17 May 2000, and was celebrated with a [[friendly match]] between [[Middlesbrough F.C.]] and [[A.S. Bari]]. This ground has hosted matches at international level, and the most celebrated results on this ground were won by the likes of [[Almadina S.C.|Al Madina]], who defeated [[ES Tunis]] 2-1, and on 19 September 2006, [[Al Ittihad Tripoli|Al Ittihad]] defeated [[Al-Nahda (Omani football club)|Al Nahdha]] of [[Oman]] in the 2006-07 [[Arab Champions League]].
