{{Spanish name|Vargas|Velázquez}} {{Infobox gymnast | name = Luis Vargas | gender = m | image = | image_size = | caption = | fullname = Luis Felipe Vargas Velázquez | altname = | nickname = Tingui | country = {{PUR}} | regions = | formercountry = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|6|8}} | birth_place = [[Río Piedras, Puerto Rico]] | hometown = | residence = | death_date = | death_place = | height = | discipline = MAG | level = Senior International Elite | natlteam = 1999–2011 | club = | gym = | collegeteam = | headcoach = | assistcoach = | formercoach = | choreographer = | music = | eponymousskills = | retired = | worldranking = | updated = | show-medals = yes | medaltemplates = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] --> {{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }} {{MedalSilver | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2011 Pan American Games|Parallel bars]] }} {{MedalSilver | [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2011 Pan American Games|Team]] }} }}
'''Luis Felipe Vargas Velázquez''' (born June 8, 1983) is a Puerto Rican male [[artistic gymnast]] and part of the national team. He participated at [[2004 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/va/luis-vargas-1.html |title=Luis Vargas |access-date=17 October 2016}}</ref> He also competed at world championships, including the [[2010 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] in Rotterdam, the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |title=2010 World Gymnastics Championships athletes – Luis Vargas Velazquez |url=http://gym.longinestiming.com/File/000009010200FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF02 |work=longinestiming.com |date= |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>
==Education==
Luis Vargas completed a Master's Degree in Health Promotion at the [[University of Turabo]] (UT) in Puerto Rico, USA.
