'''Robotniczy Klub Sportowy „Skała"''' ('Workers Sport Club "Rock"', abbreviated '''RKS''') was a [[Jew]]ish [[Communist]] sports organization in [[Wyszków]], Poland, active during the [[interbellum]] years. Founded in 1928, RKS was one of two Jewish sports organizations in the city (the other being [[Maccabi (sports)|Makabi]]).<ref name="z">Polska Zjednoczona Partia Robotnicza (Poland). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=qDVDAQAAIAAJ Z Pola Walki. Kwartalnik Poświęcony Dziejom Ruchu Robotniczego]''. 1983. p. 119</ref><ref name="w">Baker, Zachary M., Jonathan Boyarin, and Jack Kugelmass. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=MHCpUsgZm3EC&pg=PA89 From a Ruined Garden: The Memorial Books of Polish Jewry]''. Bloomington, Ind: Indiana University Press, 1998. p. 89</ref> The club had a football team.<ref name="w"/>
RKS had initially appealed to Jewish workers across party lines, with the slogan that "...if you are a worker, you belong in this club". However, the political unity became short-lived.<ref name="w"/> The communists seized control over the club.<ref>Szczepański, Janusz. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=O5SgAAAAMAAJ Dzieje Spolecznosci Zydowskiej: Powiatow Pultusk I Makow Mazowiecki]''. Warszawa: Zaklad Wydawniczy Letter Quality, 1993. p. 109</ref> Just a few weeks after its foundation, the [[Poale Zion Left]] followers split away and set up a third Jewish sports organization in the city (Gwiazda).<ref name="w"/>
RKS had more than 200 members (100 men, 70 women and 40 children).<ref>Krzemień, Leszek. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=vAcFAAAAMAAJ Związek młodzieży komunistycznej w Polsce; pierwsze dziesięciolecie (1918–1928)]''. Warszawa: Książka i Wiedza, 1972. p. 287</ref> Its members were largely from the [[Central Jewish Bureau, Communist Party of Poland|Jewish Section]] of the [[Communist Party of Poland|Communist Party]].<ref>Brenner, Michael, and Gideon Reuveni. ''Emancipation Through Muscles: Jews and Sports in Europe''. [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]]: University of Nebraska Press, 2006. p. 94, 99</ref> However, there were also some unaffiliated workers that remained as members of the club.<ref name="w"/>
