{{sport overview | image = <!-- image filename and type (i.e. "ImageName.png" --> | imagesize = <!-- change image size, default is 200px. must add units afterward, i.e. "250px" not "250" --> | image_alt = <!-- alt text, which will be seen when hovering over the image --> | caption = <!-- caption for the image above --> | union = [[Swimming Federation of India]] | country = India | sport = water polo | teamlabel1 = <!-- overrides the "National team" label with custom label --> | nationalteam = [[India men's national water polo team|India]] | nickname = <!-- nicknames --> | first = <!-- date first played --> | registered = <!-- number of registered players --> | clubs = <!-- number of clubs --> | national_list = <!-- list of national competitions --> | club_list = <!-- list of club competitions --> | intl_list = {{collapsible list| Asian Games: * Champions 1981 * Runners up 1970 * 3rd place 1982 * Women 4th place 2010}} | match = <!-- single match audience record --> | league = <!-- league audience record --> }}
'''Water polo in India''' is administered by the [[Swimming Federation of India]]. India's best performance was when they won gold at the [[Water polo at the 1951 Asian Games|1951 Asian Games]]. The [[India men's national water polo team]] also won a silver medal at the [[1970 Asian Games]], losing to [[Japan men's national water polo team|Japan]] 4 goals to 3 in the finals.<ref name="TOI - 30Nov2010 - When Indian won a silver in Asiad water polo">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-30/others/28217409_1_water-polo-asiad-gold-asia-xi|title=When Indian won a silver in Asiad water polo|last=Vijaykar|first=Pradeep|date=Nov 30, 2010|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=5 May 2012}}</ref> The next time India won a medal was a bronze at the [[1982 Asian Games]].
== Management == Water Polo in India is administered by the [[Swimming Federation of India]] (SFI).
== India's Men's Team at the Olympics == India has participated twice at the [[Olympic Games|Olympics]]. {| class="wikitable" !Year !Rank !Venue !Round One Results !Round Two Results |- |1948 |9-12<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1948 Summer Olympics|date=2018-05-19|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1948_Summer_Olympics&oldid=842032223|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |[[Finchley Lido]] |IND 1:12 NED IND 7:4 CHI |IND 1:12 NED IND 1:11 ESP |- |1952 |17-21<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1952 Summer Olympics|date=2017-12-29|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1952_Summer_Olympics&oldid=817675704|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |[[Helsinki Swimming Stadium]] | - | - |}
== India's Men's Team at the Asian Games == India has participated 5 times at the [[Asian Games]]. {| class="wikitable" !Year !Rank !Venue |- |1951 |1<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1951 Asian Games|date=2018-05-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1951_Asian_Games&oldid=839504336|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |New Delhi, India |- |1970 |2<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1970 Asian Games|date=2018-05-04|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1970_Asian_Games&oldid=839524346|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |Bangkok, Thailand |- |1974 |6<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1974 Asian Games|date=2018-06-05|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1974_Asian_Games&oldid=844524166|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |Tehran, Iran |- |1982 |3<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1982 Asian Games|date=2018-05-04|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1982_Asian_Games&oldid=839524507|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |New Delhi, India |- |1986 |6<ref>{{Citation|title=Water polo at the 1986 Asian Games|date=2018-05-04|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Water_polo_at_the_1986_Asian_Games&oldid=839525372|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> |Seoul, South Korea |}
== India's Men's National Team == As of July, 2018, as per the [[Swimming Federation of India]] (SFI)'s announcement of team<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/others/sfi-announces-indian-swimming-squad-for-asian-games/articleshow/64807680.cms|title=SFI announces Indian swimming squad for Asian Games - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-06-30}}</ref> for the [[2018 Asian Games|Asian Games]], the team stood as follows:
Aneesh Babu (GK), Akshay Kumar Kunde, Ashwini Kumar Kunde, Adarsh VS, Uday Uttekar, Prithish Das, Sarang Vaidya, Aneesh Kumar, Karthik Ch Das, Shibin Lal, Manimaran D, S Ratheesh Kumar, Monjith Hasan, Lal Krishna and J Shreejith.
However, later the [[Indian Olympic Association]] decided against sending the [[India men's national water polo team|Men's National Water polo team]] to the [[2018 Asian Games]].
